## Best Practices

1. **Start Simple**: Begin with intuition before diving into formalism
2. **Be Precise**: Use correct mathematical notation and terminology
3. **Provide Context**: Explain when and why to use each concept
4. **Address Misconceptions**: Explicitly call out common mistakes
5. **Link Concepts**: Show how topics connect to broader statistical theory
6. **Use Visualizations**: Suggest or create plots to illustrate concepts
7. **Make it Accessible**: Balance rigor with readability

## Example Output Template

```html
<article>
  <h1>Understanding the Central Limit Theorem</h1>
  
  <p class="introduction">
    One of the most powerful results in statistics is the Central Limit Theorem (CLT), 
    which explains why the normal distribution appears so frequently in nature and 
    statistical practice.
  </p>
  
  <h2>The Theorem</h2>
  
  <p>
    The Central Limit Theorem states that the sum (or average) of a large number of 
    independent, identically distributed random variables will be approximately normally 
    distributed, regardless of the original distribution.
  </p>
  
  <p>
    Formally, let $X_1, X_2, \ldots, X_n$ be independent random variables with mean 
    $\mu$ and variance $\sigma^2$. Define the sample mean:
  </p>
  
  $$
  \bar{X}_n = \frac{1}{n}\sum_{i=1}^{n} X_i
  $$
  
  <p>
    Then as $n \to \infty$, the standardized sample mean converges in distribution 
    to a standard normal:
  </p>
  
  $$
  \frac{\bar{X}_n - \mu}{\sigma/\sqrt{n}} \xrightarrow{d} \mathcal{N}(0, 1)
  $$
  
  <h2>Why This Matters</h2>
  
  <p>
    The CLT is the foundation for many statistical methods including:
  </p>
  
  <ul>
    <li>Confidence intervals for means</li>
    <li>Hypothesis testing</li>
    <li>Quality control charts</li>
    <li>Survey sampling</li>
  </ul>
  
  <!-- Continue with examples, visualizations, etc. -->
  
</article>
```

## Common Pitfalls to Avoid

1. **Notation Confusion**: Always define variables before using them
2. **Circular Definitions**: Don't define terms using themselves
3. **Missing Assumptions**: State when theorems apply and when they don't
4. **Oversimplification**: Balance accessibility with mathematical correctness
5. **No Context**: Always explain why the concept matters

